<paragraph blockId="1.[151,824,1338,1365]" box="[151,824,1338,1365]" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,824,1338,1365]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,824,1338,1365]" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">
Biology of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chlidoplitis" authorityName="Chlidoplitis" box="[284,547,1338,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[284,380,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Hoplitis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[397,537,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Chlidoplitis</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[609,640,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[656,814,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Megahoplitis</emphasis>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1409,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">
Although the low number of pollen loads analyzed so far renders the assessment of the degree of specialization premature for several species (see species accounts), current knowledge suggests that all 
<emphasis box="[1165,1351,1445,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. (Chlidoplitis)</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. (Megahoplitis</emphasis>
) species are pollen specialists. Species of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[989,1121,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Chlidoplitis</emphasis>
are probably all narrowly oligolectic exhibiting distinct or even exclusive preferences for widely different and unrelated plant taxa, such as 
<taxonomicName box="[151,226,1553,1578]" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,226,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Allium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[241,352,1553,1578]" class="Liliopsida" family="Alliaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="family">Alliaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[373,533,1553,1578]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Haplophyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[373,533,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Haplophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[549,657,1554,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rutaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[678,759,1553,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Resedaceae" genus="Reseda" kingdom="Plantae" order="Capparales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[678,759,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Reseda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[775,912,1553,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Resedaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Capparales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Resedaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[932,1036,1554,1577]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Teucrium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1036,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Teucrium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1053,1180,1553,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lamiaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[1200,1304,1553,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Trifolium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1304,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Trifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1320,1428,1553,1578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) or 
<taxonomicName box="[183,314,1589,1614]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Hedysareae">Hedysareae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[330,441,1589,1614]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[460,635,1589,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrina">
<emphasis box="[460,635,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Hoplitis tigrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, one of the two representatives of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1190,1338,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Megahoplitis</emphasis>
, is most probably oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName box="[431,572,1625,1650]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carduoideae">Carduoideae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[592,721,1626,1650]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
), whereas the pollen host preferences of its sister species 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bombiformis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. bombiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are still unknown; the only pollen load available so far suggests that this latter species might also be a specialist of 
<taxonomicName box="[292,438,1697,1722]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carduoideae">Carduoideae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1409,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">
Observations on nesting site and nest building material are available for two species of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[151,283,1769,1794]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Chlidoplitis</emphasis>
(see species accounts), which, however, do not provide a consistent picture on the overall nesting biology of this subgenus. Both 
<taxonomicName authority="Zanden" authorityName="Zanden" box="[498,786,1805,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heinrichi">
<emphasis box="[498,696,1805,1830]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Hoplitis heinrichi</emphasis>
Zanden
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Friese" authorityName="Friese" box="[839,1062,1805,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lysholmi">
<emphasis box="[839,968,1805,1830]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. lysholmi</emphasis>
(Friese)
</taxonomicName>
were observed to nest in burrows excavated by other insects in the soil, suggesting that preexisting ground burrows might be the usual nesting site of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[309,441,1877,1902]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Chlidoplitis</emphasis>
. Whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[567,705,1877,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heinrichi">
<emphasis box="[567,705,1877,1902]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. heinrichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found to build both entire brood cells and partitions from masticated leaves (
<figureCitation box="[365,434,1913,1938]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">
Fig. 
<number box="[418,434,1914,1938]" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[457,587,1913,1938]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lysholmi">
<emphasis box="[457,587,1913,1938]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H. lysholmi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was observed to close its nests with mud, suggesting that 
<emphasis box="[1250,1278,1914,1937]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1294,1426,1913,1938]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Chlidoplitis</emphasis>
) species might differ in their choice of nesting material. No information on the nesting biology of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[151,299,1985,2010]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="162">Megahoplitis</emphasis>
exists.
</paragraph>
